             (Police-constable N 168). I was on duty in Upper-street, Islington, at half-past one o'clock in the morning of the 26th of August; I saw the prisoner carrying a goose, and took him into custody - he was half a mile from the prosecutor's.</p>
               <p>ESQUIRE DUKE. I know this goose to be mine; I had seen it safe the morning before, in a little paddock at the back of my house - I do not know the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I saw a man on Highgate-hill with some geese in a cart - his trace broke, and he asked me if I had a bit of string; I lent him a bit - a man came and asked if the geese were for sale; he said Yes, they were 3s. each: I said I would have one for half a crown and bought it.</p>
